1
00:00:23,908 --> 00:00:24,670
Good evening.

2
00:00:24,730 --> 00:00:26,792
I trust you've had a fruitful day.

3
00:00:27,013 --> 00:00:30,077
I do not say happy, but I do hope it has been happy.

4
00:00:30,097 --> 00:00:31,439
The sun's come out too.

5
00:00:32,820 --> 00:00:49,241
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambho Dasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambho Dasa

6
00:00:50,064 --> 00:00:58,393
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa.

7
00:00:58,914 --> 00:01:02,957
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble, and fully self-awakened one.

8
00:01:05,379 --> 00:01:08,722
So we're still struggling through the taints.

9
00:01:12,007 --> 00:01:17,371
There's seven of them, the seven ways of overcoming the taints.

10
00:01:17,521 --> 00:01:28,393
So we've done the first one, of course, which is all about Vipassana, really, and seeing this whole business of the self, of identity.

11
00:01:28,453 --> 00:01:30,936
Then we did by using the taint.

12
00:01:30,956 --> 00:01:32,938
I think I'm right.

13
00:01:34,319 --> 00:01:34,959
No, I'm not.

14
00:01:35,079 --> 00:01:35,941
By restraining.

15
00:01:36,021 --> 00:01:37,141
Screws me.

16
00:01:37,162 --> 00:01:37,903
Just a minute.

17
00:01:37,923 --> 00:01:38,903
I'm getting confused here.

18
00:01:40,146 --> 00:01:40,805
See, that's right.

19
00:01:40,825 --> 00:01:41,246
We did that.

20
00:01:41,667 --> 00:01:43,308
So remember there are...

21
00:01:43,474 --> 00:01:54,469
The taint should be abandoned by seeing, restraining, by using, by enduring, by avoiding, and by removing, and finally by developing.

22
00:01:55,350 --> 00:01:59,736
So we've moved from seeing to restraining.

23
00:02:01,459 --> 00:02:04,022
So we're now on to abandon by using.

24
00:02:04,743 --> 00:02:06,867
Okay, so this is the passage.

25
00:02:10,913 --> 00:02:14,501
What taint should be abandoned by using?

26
00:02:15,203 --> 00:02:21,937
Here, now remember that these discourses are remembered by the monastics and basically for monastics.

27
00:02:22,538 --> 00:02:27,049
So we have to translate it into daily life.

28
00:02:31,703 --> 00:02:47,189
using the robe only for protection from the cold, from protection from heat, from contact with gadflies, mosquitoes, wind, the sun, the creeping things, and only for the purpose of concealing the private parts.

29
00:02:47,751 --> 00:02:49,354
Very forward, isn't he?

30
00:02:50,175 --> 00:02:53,762
So here he's given us the reason for...

31
00:02:53,741 --> 00:02:59,872
Wearing clothes, right, is obviously for protection, warmth of the body and so on and so forth.

32
00:03:00,432 --> 00:03:02,074
But not for really for anything else.

33
00:03:02,475 --> 00:03:05,860
Now, that doesn't particularly work for lay people.

34
00:03:05,920 --> 00:03:10,147
You've got to dress according to where you are at work.

35
00:03:10,127 --> 00:03:26,770
at play with the family and so on and so forth but there's an interesting thing that happened when the order was first established when people joined him both monks and nuns they would go to the charnel grounds

36
00:03:26,750 --> 00:03:34,362
And dead bodies then were wrapped up in white cloth and just left, left to be eaten by wild animals, etc.

37
00:03:35,163 --> 00:03:45,700
And it was the general custom of the salmoners, these people who had left the lay life to live an ascetic life with various teachers.

38
00:03:46,201 --> 00:03:51,069
It was the custom to go and take this cloth and turn it into robes.

39
00:03:52,027 --> 00:03:58,581
and sew little bits together to make a lower robe and an upper robe.

40
00:04:00,044 --> 00:04:07,640
Now, the first thing was that he himself decided that it didn't look so good.

41
00:04:08,295 --> 00:04:16,511
So he asked the monks to cut the pieces so that when the robe was laid out, it looked like paddy fields.

42
00:04:17,151 --> 00:04:27,250
So if you ever see a monk's robe laid out, you'll see that there are large patches for the paddy and little passages all around it.

43
00:04:27,730 --> 00:04:28,752
And they're all measured out.

44
00:04:28,793 --> 00:04:30,776
They're all meant to be of a certain measure.

45
00:04:31,297 --> 00:04:36,603
And that way the robes didn't look so untidy.

46
00:04:36,644 --> 00:04:44,432
On top of that, he asked them to dye it in the arakanat, which gives it a sort of light brown color.

47
00:04:45,014 --> 00:04:54,665
And that's why monks' robes and nuns' robes are all this some form of shade of brown, warm brown, red brown, all that sort of stuff.

48
00:04:54,685 --> 00:04:59,851
And it all comes back to the Buddha wanting his order to look neat.

49
00:05:00,202 --> 00:05:04,807
So it's not as though he's saying you should just wear scruffy clothes.

50
00:05:05,548 --> 00:05:28,033
You should wear things that you feel comfortable with, both from the point of view of the climate and the situation you're in, but also in terms of how it fits your understanding of, shall we say, natural beauty, not something forced constantly by fashion, constantly changing by fashion.

51
00:05:28,012 --> 00:05:30,476
although that has obviously something to do with it.

52
00:05:31,819 --> 00:05:39,290
But it's again this wonderful practicality that the Buddha has, you know, constantly asking, what are clothes for?

53
00:05:40,252 --> 00:05:54,375
And then, of course, there's the amount of clothes that we have, and that's to do with what is need rather than greed, or what is, shall we say, allowable by just common sense,

54
00:05:54,355 --> 00:05:56,978
So one needs various pair of shoes in the West.

55
00:05:57,439 --> 00:06:00,985
In the East, a monk or nun might just get away with slippers.

56
00:06:01,045 --> 00:06:02,326
Some actually go barefoot.

57
00:06:03,327 --> 00:06:09,396
But here you need, if you want to go walking, you need boots and then you need slippers and then you need shoes, you need all sorts of things.

58
00:06:10,298 --> 00:06:15,165
So it's all to do with where we are, but being practical, being practical.

59
00:06:18,149 --> 00:06:31,968
And modesty, of course, runs high in the Buddhist teachings because we're trying to reduce the desire for our sexual appetite.

60
00:06:32,428 --> 00:06:41,000
So that's why nuns and monks especially robe themselves in very loose robes so that the body is not so obvious.

61
00:06:42,904 --> 00:06:46,490
So that's this business of wearing robes.

62
00:06:46,769 --> 00:06:52,057
These paragraphs that I'll be reading are chanted by monks as a reminder.

63
00:06:55,442 --> 00:06:56,884
Then we come to alms food.

64
00:06:57,545 --> 00:07:10,262
He uses alms food neither for amusement or for intoxication, nor for the sake of physical beauty or attractiveness, but only for the endurance and continuance of this body or ending

65
00:07:10,242 --> 00:07:25,298
discomfort for ending discomfort and for assisting in the holy life considering thus i shall terminate old feelings without arousing new feelings and i shall be healthy blameless and shall live in comfort

66
00:07:25,278 --> 00:07:30,706
So here again, it's just the practicality of eating for the nourishment of the body.

67
00:07:30,725 --> 00:07:34,009
Now, you have to be careful.

68
00:07:34,089 --> 00:07:37,475
He didn't tell lay people what to offer him.

69
00:07:38,156 --> 00:07:44,084
If he went to kings, if he was invited by kings or rich people, they would obviously give him very special dishes.

70
00:07:44,725 --> 00:07:46,127
And he never complained about that.

71
00:07:46,206 --> 00:07:47,889
That was an offering that they could give.

72
00:07:47,928 --> 00:07:50,593
So he was quite happy to receive it.

73
00:07:50,572 --> 00:07:56,281
On the other hand, if he was wandering just in ordinary villages, he might have some very basic food.

74
00:07:56,802 --> 00:07:58,684
And of course, at that time, they had famines.

75
00:07:59,125 --> 00:07:59,846
They had famines.

76
00:08:03,230 --> 00:08:10,380
When I went out to Thailand, for instance, I was up at Wat Phanana Shack, just for a visit.

77
00:08:10,821 --> 00:08:11,983
I was there for about two weeks.

78
00:08:12,362 --> 00:08:17,069
And we would go off on alms round.

79
00:08:17,572 --> 00:08:22,858
And I also did it with Ajahn Mahabua's place up in the northeast.

80
00:08:23,519 --> 00:08:26,423
And we went on our round to the villages in the morning.

81
00:08:27,283 --> 00:08:35,091
And basically, all we were offered was what they could, which was rice, with little bits of meat sometimes, a bit of fish or something.

82
00:08:36,092 --> 00:08:37,575
Basically, it was just rice.

83
00:08:38,596 --> 00:08:45,724
And it was only when we got back to the monastery that the local richer middle class had supplied us with...

84
00:08:46,075 --> 00:08:47,240
abundant food.

85
00:08:47,481 --> 00:08:54,515
So there's a huge disparity as it is everywhere in the world these days between the rich and the poor.

86
00:08:55,019 --> 00:09:00,570
But there would have been times during the Buddha's time when there were actual famines.

87
00:09:01,230 --> 00:09:08,346
And the mendicants would have been right at the end of the line, of course, you know, except for devotees.

88
00:09:08,405 --> 00:09:16,621
That was the devotee would obviously try to make sure that the people whom they honored would have enough food.

89
00:09:18,086 --> 00:09:22,313
But again, it's not eating for any other purpose.

90
00:09:22,615 --> 00:09:25,759
That's the real thing for the nourishment of the body.

91
00:09:26,160 --> 00:09:30,006
Now, it doesn't mean to say that the food has to be plain or horrible.

92
00:09:30,508 --> 00:09:34,053
It's just that that's where your intention is.

93
00:09:34,033 --> 00:09:38,261
to feed, nourish the body for the purpose of spiritual practice.

94
00:09:38,682 --> 00:09:42,029
That doesn't mean to say that you can't cook yourself a pleasant meal.

95
00:09:42,410 --> 00:09:55,636
So these days where many of us are in isolation, that's one way of raising your heart, raising your spirit to make an effort to cook for yourself, to care for yourself and to give something which is appetizing.

96
00:09:55,616 --> 00:10:01,876
How much you eat, of course, will be determined by feeding your appetite or feeding your greed.

97
00:10:02,158 --> 00:10:04,767
So that's the distinction we have to make.

98
00:10:05,610 --> 00:10:08,799
What we eat is not so important.

99
00:10:11,597 --> 00:10:16,206
And the whole thing is, of course, is to reduce this greed.

100
00:10:16,225 --> 00:10:26,403
Now, remember that often we eat not just because we enjoy it and indulge it because of that, but also we're hiding from ourselves feelings that we don't want.

101
00:10:26,864 --> 00:10:33,235
So many, many of you, shall we say, who are living completely alone in isolation,

102
00:10:33,586 --> 00:10:39,822
Might find the evenings difficult, you know, loneliness might come, a bit of depression, etc.

103
00:10:40,543 --> 00:10:46,317
And one way that we seek is, of course, to get up a toast, buttered toast.

104
00:10:46,378 --> 00:10:49,164
I mean, you know, well, that is the cure.

105
00:10:49,144 --> 00:10:55,394
But unfortunately, it hides from us these painful mental states.

106
00:10:55,975 --> 00:11:07,272
So what is better to do is to sit with that for a while, you know, to sit with it and wait for it to exhaust itself or at least to diminish, to diminish.

107
00:11:07,690 --> 00:11:13,859
And then to, as it were, congratulate ourselves that we haven't just given into it to try and get rid of it.

108
00:11:14,419 --> 00:11:17,264
We can then congratulate ourselves with a piece of toast.

109
00:11:17,524 --> 00:11:24,115
See, you can rejoice that you overcame a negative reason for having toast.

110
00:11:24,434 --> 00:11:25,496
You're now celebrating.

111
00:11:26,489 --> 00:11:49,729
feast days are there for celebration it's a way of expressing joy or praise or wonder it's a way of thanking everybody so in in as you know in buddhist countries there are two main times which is buddha day where we're celebrating the the life of the buddha and that's coming up

112
00:11:50,013 --> 00:11:54,957
I mean, we would have run a course now at the beginning of May, but for this virus.

113
00:11:55,739 --> 00:11:59,363
And that's a place where we would celebrate.

114
00:11:59,442 --> 00:12:04,207
So people bring lovely food, not only for the monastics, but for themselves.

115
00:12:05,068 --> 00:12:11,335
And the other time is the Sangha Day, the Katina, where the Sangha is celebrated.

116
00:12:11,355 --> 00:12:15,700
And that's normally a time when people bring things that the Sangha might need.

117
00:12:16,152 --> 00:12:24,190
So these two occasions are, shall we say, a community effort to celebrate and food is very much part of it.

118
00:12:26,475 --> 00:12:27,857
So there's nothing wrong with feasting.

119
00:12:27,957 --> 00:12:28,980
That's what I say anyway.

120
00:12:31,610 --> 00:12:34,957
So then we go on to reflecting wisely.

121
00:12:34,977 --> 00:12:35,919
It's always a reflecting.

122
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:40,350
Remember this, this, there's been some yoni so manesikara.

123
00:12:40,370 --> 00:12:46,884
It's a very constant phrase of the Buddha, just, you know, to sit and think about things, to reflect upon things.

124
00:12:47,287 --> 00:13:03,570
He uses a resting place only for protection from cold, for protection from heat, protection from gadflies, mosquitoes, wind, the sun, creeping things, and only for the purpose of warding off the perils of climate and for enjoying retreat.

125
00:13:04,130 --> 00:13:07,596
So here he's talking about a place where you stay.

126
00:13:08,035 --> 00:13:16,347
So in the East, the monks can be happy with just a little hut somewhere.

127
00:13:16,666 --> 00:13:19,812
I was very fortunate when I stayed at Kenda Boulder.

128
00:13:19,871 --> 00:13:22,317
I had an eight foot by five foot.

129
00:13:22,636 --> 00:13:23,357
That's about what?

130
00:13:23,839 --> 00:13:29,450
Two and a half meters by one and three quarter meters.

131
00:13:30,672 --> 00:13:32,095
Little space there.

132
00:13:32,434 --> 00:13:33,456
It was very comfortable.

133
00:13:33,638 --> 00:13:35,561
All I needed was a bed and a chair.

134
00:13:35,620 --> 00:13:37,644
And that was about it.

135
00:13:38,029 --> 00:13:40,855
And that was enough for that particular time.

136
00:13:41,316 --> 00:13:45,203
Now, of course, I need mobiles and all sorts of silly things.

137
00:13:45,224 --> 00:13:47,768
But in those days, it was extremely simple.

138
00:13:47,969 --> 00:13:50,774
And that simplicity brings with it a great sense of peace.

139
00:13:50,793 --> 00:13:52,037
You don't have to worry about anything.

140
00:13:52,057 --> 00:13:54,942
You don't have to worry about whether you have Wi-Fi or not.

141
00:13:57,621 --> 00:14:00,988
And again, to be very practical.

142
00:14:01,087 --> 00:14:03,753
What's the purpose of your house, of your flat?

143
00:14:04,232 --> 00:14:05,414
What's the purpose of your room?

144
00:14:05,916 --> 00:14:06,977
What's the purpose of it?

145
00:14:07,399 --> 00:14:08,620
And to keep it very simple.

146
00:14:09,543 --> 00:14:14,971
As soon as we add things, as soon as we make things more complicated, then the worries come.

147
00:14:15,491 --> 00:14:18,298
you know, the worry of loss and all that sort of stuff.

148
00:14:19,100 --> 00:14:25,774
So try and keep things simple by reflecting what's the purpose of a dwelling?

149
00:14:25,833 --> 00:14:27,658
What is the purpose of this room?

150
00:14:27,697 --> 00:14:29,822
I mean, what's the purpose of my bedroom?

151
00:14:33,565 --> 00:14:39,272
And enjoying retreats, well, that of course is a monastic thing about seclusion, not isolation.

152
00:14:40,413 --> 00:14:54,831
But it's always good, remember, to have a regular place in your house, in your flat, wherever you're living, which you have partitioned off in some way where you go to in order to practice, in order to meditate.

153
00:14:54,811 --> 00:14:59,696
That also helps with creating this habit because it's there as a place.

154
00:15:00,297 --> 00:15:05,523
It's the same as when we have temples or here where we have the stupa.

155
00:15:05,883 --> 00:15:07,625
They remind you.

156
00:15:08,365 --> 00:15:08,927
It's there.

157
00:15:08,947 --> 00:15:18,957
You see, you've got your, if you have a statue, if you like statues, but definitely some place in the house where you have established a certain atmosphere.

158
00:15:18,977 --> 00:15:21,561
So that's important.

159
00:15:24,746 --> 00:15:35,121
And then finally, of course, to use wisely medicinal requisites only for the protection of arisen afflicting feelings and for the benefit of good health.

160
00:15:36,102 --> 00:15:42,552
So again, medicine, you know, to use it for the benefit of the body.

161
00:15:43,232 --> 00:15:46,096
This one I think is easy enough to understand.

162
00:15:46,076 --> 00:15:50,988
But often we are, these days we've become very neurotic about things.

163
00:15:51,128 --> 00:15:53,914
I never used to take vitamin pills.

164
00:15:54,296 --> 00:15:57,241
Now I'm taking vitamin pills and quercetin.

165
00:15:57,702 --> 00:16:01,572
I'm just sort of, I'm piling this stuff into my body and I

166
00:16:03,019 --> 00:16:10,149
I'm coming to a point where I must, you know, I've determined to stop all that stuff because the body knows how to care for itself.

167
00:16:10,169 --> 00:16:18,480
And it's not, if it's not in a good way, then it'll tell you, you know, the food we get, people complain about it, this and that in it.

168
00:16:18,541 --> 00:16:21,264
But the fact is that generally speaking, we're living longer.

169
00:16:21,548 --> 00:16:22,830
And we're living more healthy.

170
00:16:22,929 --> 00:16:24,793
So we must have got something right.

171
00:16:25,394 --> 00:16:34,527
And usually a lot of diseases that we have are caused by not eating the right things, by eating sugary things.

172
00:16:34,547 --> 00:16:37,731
That's why we've got all this diabetes stuff.

173
00:16:38,493 --> 00:16:40,777
So it's not that I don't think it's so much to do with the food.

174
00:16:41,177 --> 00:16:44,101
I'm sure I can hear many of you complaining about that now.

175
00:16:44,201 --> 00:16:51,032
But in my understanding, I have no complaint with the food that we get from the shops.

176
00:16:53,527 --> 00:16:55,950
So seeing food as medicine, that's the other thing too.

177
00:16:56,009 --> 00:17:00,275
Food as a nourishment for the body, that's also part of this.

178
00:17:00,296 --> 00:17:17,199
Of course, that will remind us of this special medicine, Ayurvedic medicine, of which, if you remember, there was the story of the Zen monk who was cured with cow's urine.

179
00:17:17,700 --> 00:17:18,740
See, so that's...

180
00:17:19,597 --> 00:17:23,002
Fermented, fermented cow's urine, yeah?

181
00:17:23,022 --> 00:17:26,749
So make sure it's fermented when you get some, okay?

182
00:17:28,070 --> 00:17:41,510
So the taints which create vexation and fever might arise in one who does not use these requisites wisely, yeah?

183
00:17:41,530 --> 00:17:45,497
So it's a case of being careful how we use things.

184
00:17:45,817 --> 00:17:48,541
Now, you can extend this to everything you use.

185
00:17:48,521 --> 00:17:54,749
the television, the mobile, your computer.

186
00:17:56,731 --> 00:17:58,534
Why are you using it at this time?

187
00:17:58,713 --> 00:17:59,674
What are you looking at?

188
00:17:59,694 --> 00:18:00,876
What's the purpose of it?

189
00:18:01,336 --> 00:18:05,843
And make sure that it is actually for Dharma purposes.

190
00:18:06,083 --> 00:18:14,692
Now, if it's not for Dharma purposes, if it's for something that you see as unwholesome, be truthful to yourself, be truthful to ourselves.

191
00:18:15,233 --> 00:18:17,836
When I'm doing something which I know,

192
00:18:17,817 --> 00:18:21,800
I know it's not quite right, you know, it's like, I know it's quite...

193
00:18:21,820 --> 00:18:25,005
There will be consequences, there will be consequences.

194
00:18:25,665 --> 00:18:29,108
And it's being truthful to ourselves about what we're doing.

195
00:18:29,869 --> 00:18:40,162
And if we see that we're doing something which is not good for us, you know, to just keep making the resolution, make the resolution, make the resolution.

196
00:18:40,481 --> 00:18:42,423
And eventually it comes through, yeah?

197
00:18:42,403 --> 00:18:53,480
But remember, with all these things that are tempting, it's always good to try and just sit with the feeling of it, sit with the feeling of it and wait for it to exhaust itself.

198
00:18:54,383 --> 00:19:00,070
And then it gives you a feeling of power that you can actually control these habits.

199
00:19:01,232 --> 00:19:02,454
That's also important.

200
00:19:04,071 --> 00:19:12,219
So we've completed today the abandoning of these taints by using things wisely.

201
00:19:12,259 --> 00:19:16,393
So this obviously only refers to certain things that we have and use.

202
00:19:20,035 --> 00:19:24,563
So we'll carry on tomorrow to the next one because each one has something to teach us.

203
00:19:24,923 --> 00:19:25,324
Okay.

204
00:19:26,165 --> 00:19:32,556
So I hope that's been useful in some way and that you've not found it completely useless.

205
00:19:33,178 --> 00:19:36,563
And I think it's time for us to do some meditation.

206
00:19:36,583 --> 00:19:36,963
Very good.

